{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"354434eb-4a13-486d-9e4a-6a7ae9abb7a8","content":"## Debugging a C# MCP Server with MCP Inspector\n\n**1. Install & launch the Inspector:**\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector\n```\nThis opens a web UI (typically at `http://localhost:6274`).\n\n**2. Configure the connection:**\n- **Transport Type:** `STDIO`\n- **Command:** `dotnet`\n- **Args:** `run --project /path/to/YourServer.csproj`\n\n  *(Or point to a built DLL: command `dotnet`, args `/path/to/YourServer.dll`)*\n\n**3. Click \"Connect\"** — the Inspector spawns your process, negotiates the MCP handshake over stdin/stdout, and shows available tools, resources, and prompts.\n\n**4. Test interactively:**\n- Go to the **Tools** tab → click a tool → fill in parameters → **Run Tool**.\n- Check the **Console/Logs** pane for raw JSON-RPC messages to debug issues.\n\n**Key tips:**\n- Make sure your server **only** writes MCP JSON-RPC to `stdout`. Use `stderr` for any logging/diagnostics, otherwise the Inspector can't parse the stream.\n- If you use `Console.WriteLine` for debug output, switch it to `Console.Error.WriteLine`.\n- You can set environment variables in the Inspector UI if your server needs them.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"01b11397-74a2-48ef-b905-0e35c6519749","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to use the MCP Inspector to test and debug a C# MCP server that uses stdio transport. This is a general knowledge question about MCP (Model Context Protocol) tooling. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":390,"requestId":"701A:353DA2:13FF190:1732F54:69EC1161"},"id":"a5003ac3-0084-45fc-9f71-954ffb88544f","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:57:15.911Z","parentId":"7ce06281-1779-4ba6-97d7-b26b3cfd22b3"}
